**HashMap Solution in C++:**
1. We keep a Hash Map to track the elements that we have encountered till now. We mark them as true in the HashMap.
1. Just iterate over the array and check for the element (num[i]+k) and (num[i]-k) in the hash. If they are present, add it in the answer set.
1. The size of the set would be the answer. Those are the unique number of pairs with 'k' difference.
1. We need not sort the vector, and it happens in just one pass, so O(n) solution :)


```
class Solution {
public:
  int findPairs(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    set<pair<int, int>> s; 
    unordered_map <int, bool> m;
    int n = nums.size();

    for(int i=0;i<n;++i){
      if (m.find(nums[i]+k)!=m.end()){
        s.insert(make_pair(nums[i], nums[i]+k));
      }
      if (m.find(nums[i]-k)!=m.end()){
        s.insert(make_pair(nums[i]-k, nums[i]));
      }
      m[nums[i]] = true;
    }

    return s.size();
  }
};
```

