Here's the approach I used -

* Firstly, take a **string of subset of all the possible values** that can be allowed in the tinyUrl ([0-9][a-z][A-Z]).
* Then take an **unordered map** to store key value pair. (**tinyURL as key and longURL as value** ).
* Also define a **generateURL function** which generate **7 digits long tinyUrl** to assign.
* Now when encoding the URL, try to **generate the random UR**L until you find a unique URL which isn't already present in the map. then **map longUrl to this tinyUrl.**
* In decoding, simply r**eturn the longUrl stored as a value** at tinyUrl key.



```
class Solution {
public:
/* A string of subset of all the possible values that can be allowed in the tinyUrl */
string urlWord = "0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ";

/* A map to store tinyURL as key and longURL as value  */
    unordered_map<string,string> mp;
    string generateShortURL(){
        string s = "";
        for(int i=0;i<7;i++){
            s+=to_string((int)(((float)rand()/RAND_MAX)*62));
        }
        return s;
    }
    // Encodes a URL to a shortened URL.
    string encode(string longUrl) {
       string s =  generateShortURL();
	   /* checking if the tinyUrl is already present in the map or not */
        while(mp.find(s)!=mp.end()){
            s =  generateShortURL();
        }
        mp[s]=longUrl;
        return s;
    }

    // Decodes a shortened URL to its original URL.
    string decode(string shortUrl) {
       return mp[shortUrl];
    }
};

