If we use a codeword of length 6 and only small letters form English alphabet we can have roughly 309 million different combinations. It depends how fast this table will be filled but if we assume that only a smaller subset will be used we can simply use random codeword generation (with rejection if the codeword is already allocated). Otherwise we can also increment one-by-one; but I chose the simpler route here. We can also use `collections.defautdict` to check if the codeword is in use, in constant time.

```python
import random
class Codec:
    def __init__(self):
        self.lookup = collections.defaultdict(str)


    def encode(self, longUrl):
        while True:
            short = ''.join(chr(97 + random.randint(0, 25)) for _ in range(6))
            if not self.lookup[short]: break
        shortUrl = 'http://tinyurl.com/' + short
        self.lookup[shortUrl] = longUrl
        return shortUrl


    def decode(self, shortUrl):
        return self.lookup[shortUrl]
```

